iam --> who acces which resources (authorize and authenticate)

3 types of roles 
	1. basic roles 
	2. predefined roles
	3. custom roles

iam objects -->
		1. organisation 
		2. folders 
		3. projects
		4. resources 
		5. roles 
		6. members
		
	basically organisation has folders that means departments ex: deptx,depty, each department has projects for each projects has resources assigned to it 
	
basic roles:-
	1. owner  -> full administrative acces 	
	2. editor -> modify and delete access
	3. viewer -> read only access
	

compute engine IAM roles
	1. compute engine --> full access control on resources 
	2. network admin -> permissions on networking resources create,modify,delete
	3. storage admin -> permissions on storage resources like creating,modifying,delete disks,images etc..
	
	
3.Members:- 
	members are users or systems that recieves the permission
	
	types of members 
		1. user  -> user@gmial.com
		2. group  -> dev-team@company.com
		3. service accounts -> used by apps/vm's
		4. domain
		5. all users
	
4. IAM policy :- 
	iam polcy attached to a resource. it do the bindings of roles(viewer,editor,owner) and members to the resources 
	
	
5. service accounts:-
	it is used by applictions or vm's to communicate with the cloud services to access resources. for that vm's need these service accounts for authentication and authorization 
	
	Without Service Account ❌
	   VM tries to access storage → denied
	With Service Account ✅
	     VM uses service account → allowed
	     
   3 types of services accounts
   	1.user-created (custom)
   	2. built-in -> compute engine and app engine service accounts
   	3. google api service accounts
	
	
